'''Ali Ibrahim Karim Ali Al-Hamadi''' ({{langx|ar|عَلِيّ إِبْرَاهِيم كَرِيم عَلِيّ الْحَمَّادِيّ}}; born 1 March 2002) is an Iraqi professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|IpswichT}} club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. He also plays for the [[Iraq national football team|Iraq national team]].

==Biography==
Al-Hamadi was born in [[Maysan Governorate|Maysan]], Iraq, on 1 March 2002. In 2003, during the early stages of the [[Iraq War]], one year old Al-Hamadi and his family moved from Iraq to [[Toxteth]], Liverpool, where they would settle and he would grow up.<ref name="BBCfrom" /> Al-Hamadi's father, Ibrahim, who was studying to become a lawyer at that point, was part of a peaceful protest against the dictatorship of [[Saddam Hussein]] and he ended up being jailed. His wife was pregnant, and with his father's help, was released and made his way to the UK. Like most Iraqis fleeing the [[Iraq War|war]], Ali initially went to [[Jordan]] with his mother before they reunited with his father in Britain. The first time he met his father he was one-year and four-months old.<ref name=BBCfrom>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48218007|title=From Saddam Hussein to Swansea City: Striker Ali Al-Hamadi's incredible journey|date=10 May 2019|work=BBC Sport|language=English|accessdate=22 June 2020}}</ref> He is a [[Shia Muslim]].<ref>{{cite web |date=14 April 2023 |title=Realities of Ramadan |url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2023/april/realities-of-ramadan/ |access-date=14 April 2023 |publisher=AFC Wimbledon}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CLAEtACJ4yQ&t=191s|title=Ali Al-Hamadi talks Muslim Footballers off the Pitch (Ft Ali Jenabi) After Maghrib EP63|website=Youtube}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
In 2015, Al-Hamadi was selected to play for Liverpool Schoolboys at the age of 13 where he quickly made an impression and caught the attention of [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], but ended up joining [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]].<ref name=BBCfrom/> Al-Hamadi joined Tranmere's under-14s and stayed with the club for three years, being offered a professional contract in the summer of 2018 but he instead opted for a two-year scholarship at [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]'s [[Swansea City A.F.C. Under-23s|academy]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/ali-al-hamadi-i-must-keep-performing|title=Ali Al-Hamadi, I Must Keep Performing|date=15 December 2019|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |accessdate=22 June 2020}}</ref> On 2 July 2020, Al-Hamadi signed his first professional contract with Swansea, signing a one-year contract with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/swansea-city-reveal-retained-list|title=Swansea City Reveal Retained List|date=2 July 2020|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |accessdate=2 July 2020}}</ref> He was offered a new contract by Swansea in the summer of 2021 but decided to turn it down after failing to break into the first-team.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ali Al-Hamadi: The truth behind my Swansea City exit and why I felt underappreciated |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/ali-al-hamadi-truth-behind-22068285 |website=Wales Online |date=30 November 2021 |access-date=12 February 2025}}</ref> In September 2021, Al-Hamadi went on trial with [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], scoring for their [[Derby County F.C. Reserves and Academy|under-23]] side in a 3–3 [[Premier League Cup (football)|Premier League Cup]] draw against the [[Norwich City F.C. Under-23s and Academy|Norwich City under-23s]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Under23s Preview Charlton Athletic H |url=https://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/2021/10/under-23s-preview-charlton-athletic-h|access-date=29 October 2021|publisher=Derby County F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Under23s Settle For A Draw In Premier League Cup Thriller At Norwich |url=https://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/2021/09/under-23s-settle-for-a-draw-in-premier-league-cup-thriller-at-norwich|access-date=29 October 2021 |publisher=Derby County F.C.}}</ref>

===Wycombe Wanderers===
On 20 November 2021, Al-Hamadi signed an eighteen-month contract with [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]], following a successful trial period at the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ali Al-Hamadi signs for Wycombe |url=https://www.wwfc.com/news/2021/november/ali-al-hamadi-signs-for-wycombe/ |website=Wycombe Wanderers |date=20 November 2021 |access-date=12 February 2025}}</ref> On 11 March 2022, Al-Hamadi joined [[National League (division)|National League]] side [[Bromley F.C.|Bromley]] on loan until the end of the 2021–22 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wwfc.com/news/2022/march/11/ali-joins-bromley-on-loan/ |title=Ali joins Bromley on loan |publisher=Wycombe Wanderers F.C. |date=11 March 2022 |accessdate=11 March 2022}}</ref> Al-Hamadi made 11 appearances for Bromley, scoring three goals.<ref name="2021-22"/> He scored his first senior goal on 24 August 2022 in a 3–1 [[EFL Cup]] defeat against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Wycombe Wanderers 1–3 Bristol City: Kadji debut goal helps Robins progress in Carabao Cup |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62571846 |website=BBC Sport |date=24 August 2022 |access-date=12 February 2025}}</ref> After struggling for game time at [[Adams Park]] Al-Hamadi expressed a desire to seek a transfer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gareth Ainsworth explains why Ali Al-Hamadi left Wycombe for Wimbledon |url=https://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/highwycombe/23247492.gareth-ainsworth-explains-ali-al-hamadi-left-wycombe-wimbledon/ |website=Bucks Free Press |date=12 January 2023 |access-date=12 February 2025}}</ref>

===AFC Wimbledon===
On 12 January 2023, Al-Hamadi completed a permanent transfer to [[EFL League Two|League Two]] side [[AFC Wimbledon]] on a two-and-a-half-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2023/january/ali-arrives-international-forward-signs/|title=Ali arrives! International forward signs |publisher=AFC Wimbledon|date=12 January 2023|accessdate=13 January 2023}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Wimbledon on 18 February 2023 in a 2–2 draw with [[Hartlepool United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64607068 |title=Wimbledon 2–2 Hartlepool |work=BBC Sport  |date=18 February 2023 |access-date=20 February 2023}}</ref> In March 2023, he was awarded the EFL Young Player of the Month award.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cornell |first1=Rob |title=Ali targets more silverware |url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2023/july/ali-picks-up-award-and-steps-up-his-return/ |publisher=AFC Wimbledon |access-date=28 July 2023}}</ref> On 30 September, Al-Hamadi converted a hat-trick against Tranmere Rovers, his former youth club, in a 4–1 win.<ref>{{Cite news |date=30 September 2023 |title=AFC Wimbledon 4–1 Tranmere Rovers |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66898969 |access-date=2024-03-19 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was twice-awarded the PFA League Two Fans' Player of the Month award while at Wimbledon, earning the honours in March and September 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ali rewarded for stunning start |url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2023/april/ali-awarded-for-stunning-start/ |access-date=2023-12-30 |publisher=AFC Wimbledon |language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Another one! Ali wins fan award |url=https://www.afcwimbledon.co.uk/news/2023/october/another-one-ali-wins-fan-award/ |access-date=2023-12-30 |publisher=AFC Wimbledon |language=en-gb}}</ref>

===Ipswich Town===
On 29 January 2024, Al-Hamadi signed for then [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] for an undisclosed fee on a four-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2024/january/29/town-sign-striker-al-hamadi-from-AFC-Wimbledon/|title=STRIKER AL-HAMADI SIGNS|publisher=Ipswich Town F.C.|date=29 January 2024|accessdate=29 January 2024}}</ref> He made his Ipswich debut on 3 February, in a 3–2 defeat to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itfc.co.uk/news/2024/february/03/preston-north-end-v-ipswich-town-match-report/|title=PRESTON 3 TOWN 2|publisher=Ipswich Town F.C.|date=3 February 2024|access-date=4 September 2024}}</ref> On 14 February, he scored his first goal for the club, converting a penalty in stoppage time of a 4–0 away victory over [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ipswich thrash Millwall to reignite promotion bid |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68224427 |access-date=2024-02-14 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was a member of the team that achieved promotion to the [[Premier League]] [[2023–24 EFL Championship|that season]], ending a 22-year absence from the top flight.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Ipswich Town promoted to the Premier League after 22 years away |url=https://news.sky.com/story/ipswich-town-promoted-to-the-premier-league-13128893 |access-date=5 May 2024 |publisher=Sky News}}</ref> On 17 August, Al-Hamadi was brought on as a substitute during Ipswich's first match of the [[2024–25 Premier League|2024–25 season]] against Liverpool, becoming the first Iraqi footballer to play in the Premier League.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4089942|title=Al-Hamadi becomes first Iraqi to play in the Premier League|publisher=Premier League|date=20 August 2024|access-date=4 September 2024}}</ref>

On 24 January 2025, Al-Hamadi joined [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan for the remainder of the [[2024–25 Stoke City F.C. season|2024–25 season]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ali Al-Hamadi makes Potters move |url=https://www.stokecityfc.com/news/2025/january/24/ali-al-hamadi-makes-potters-move-from-ipswich-town/ |website=Stoke City |date=24 January 2025 |access-date=24 January 2025}}</ref> He scored on his debut helping Stoke to a 2–1 victory at [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hull City 1–2 Stoke City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cvg8rp9p1net |website=BBC Sport |access-date=12 February 2025}}</ref> He scored the only goal against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 12 March 2025.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stoke City 1–0 Blackburn Rovers |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c93k0le64lvt |website=BBC Sport |access-date=5 May 2025}}</ref> Al-Hamadi made 15 appearances for Stoke helping them to avoid relegation on the final day of the season.<ref name="2024-25"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Derby County 0–0 Stoke City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cddelqp53ygt |website=BBC Sport |access-date=5 May 2025}}</ref>

On 2 September 2025, Al-Hamadi joined [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on a season-long loan with an obligation to buy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ali Al-Hamadi is a Hatter! |url=https://www.lutontown.co.uk/en/news/ali-al-hamadi-is-a-hatter/ |date=2 September 2025 |access-date=2 September 2025}}</ref> After suffering a series of injuries, he scored his first goal for Luton Town against former club AFC Wimbledon on 6 April 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-04-06 |title=Al-Hamadi ends his long wait for a first Luton goal as brilliant Town dismantle AFC Wimbledon |url=https://www.lutontoday.co.uk/sport/football/luton-town/al-hamadi-ends-his-long-wait-for-a-first-luton-goal-as-brilliant-town-dismantle-afc-wimbledon-6564906 |access-date=2026-04-14 |website=Luton Today |language=en}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Al-Hamadi was eligible to play for both [[England national football team|England]] and [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] at international level and accepted a call-up to the [[Iraq national under-23 football team|Iraq U23 team]] in 2019, declaring for the country of his birth.

In late 2019, Al-Hamadi received and accepted an invitation from the Iraq under-23s to join them in their preparations for the [[2020 AFC U-23 Championship]]. Ali made his debut for and scored his first goal in October 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/traumatic-back-story-ali-al-17080131|title=The traumatic back story of Ali Al-Hamadi, the Swansea City starlet who has just done something special|date=15 October 2019|publisher=WalesOnline|language=English|accessdate=22 June 2020}}</ref> He was not included in the squad for the final tournament due to an injury he picked up at the training camp.{{Citation needed|date=November 2021}}

===Senior===
Ali received his first call-up to the senior national team in November 2021 as part of Iraq's squad for their [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC third round|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]] against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and [[Syria national football team|Syria]], with Iraq's first choice striker [[Mohanad Ali]] out injured and [[Alaa Abbas]] still regaining fitness after his injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.iq-pro.net/llldnxnxndkd/|title=اعلان_قائمة_المنتخب_العراقي|date=3 November 2021|publisher=IQPro|language=Arabic|accessdate=9 November 2021|archive-date=1 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201102200/https://www.iq-pro.net/llldnxnxndkd/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Al-Hamadi was named in the starting line-up and made his debut on 11 November in a 1–1 draw against Syria before gaining his second cap in a 3–0 loss to South Korea on 16 November, playing the full match.{{Citation needed|date=November 2021}}
	
In December 2023, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Iraq 2023 AFC Asian Cup Squad - ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/team/squad/_/id/4375/league/AFC.ASIAN.CUP |access-date=2026-04-14 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

On 31 March 2026, he scored the opening goal in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification|intercontinental play-off final]] against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] taking Iraq to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] - their first in 40 years.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 April 2026 |title=Iraq qualifies for World Cup with win over Bolivia |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-au/football/fifa-world-cup-2026/articles-video/iraq-qualifies-for-world-cup-with-win-over-bolivia-2026-04-01 |website=beIN Sports}}</ref>

